# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ailsa-craig
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The **A77 road** is a major road in Scotland.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] It runs in a southwesterly direction from the city of Glasgow, past the towns of Giffnock, Newton Mearns, Kilmarnock, Prestwick, Ayr, Girvan and Stranraer to the village of Portpatrick on the Irish Sea.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] It passes through the council areas of Glasgow City, East Renfrewshire, East Ayrshire, South Ayrshire and Dumfries and Galloway.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] It has full trunk road status from the terminus of the M77 motorway at Fenwick to the junction with the A75 in Stranraer.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Some sections - most notably those between Turnberry and Girvan, and thereon to Ballantrae, run directly on the coastline with scenic views over the Firth of Clyde and the Irish Sea.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The section between Cairnryan and Stranraer runs on the shore of Loch Ryan.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The A77 is an important link from Glasgow to one of its two major airports, Prestwick Airport, and to the two Northern Ireland ferry terminals at Cairnryan.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] As a result, the road is subject to a busy mixture of commuter, tourist and heavy goods vehicle traffic which has necessitated upgrades to many sections.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Bypasses for Ayr and Kilmarnock were built in the 1970s, and the M77 motorway replaced the Glasgow to Newton Mearns section in two stages, in the mid-to-late 1990s, but not without controversy as a section of the motorway was routed through Pollok Country Park.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] This still left the East Ayrshire and southern East Renfrewshire stretch of the road which widely appeared in statistics as one of the most dangerous sections of road in Scotland.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The majority of this section was an unsegregated, four-lane single carriageway between Kilmarnock and Newton Mearns and the lanes were narrow compared to the standard of other major roads.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] At several points, it was common for traffic waiting to turn right to queue in the overtaking lane.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The speed limit of 60 miles per hour (97 km/h) was widely ignored.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Finally, the road narrowed to only two lanes near Newton Mearns, causing long queues.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The combined result was a number of fatal crashes.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The Scottish Executive took the decision to replace the entire section up to the Kilmarnock bypass with an extension of the M77 after pressure and campaigning from West Sound and West FM.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Construction of the motorway was faster than usual, given the eagerness to replace the A77 after another fatal crash in June 2002 resulted in the death of Hugh Davidson, then Chief Inspector of Strathclyde Police, and the motorway was opened in April 2005.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] This completed a continuous dual carriageway road from Glasgow to Ayr.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The original section of the A77 between Newton Mearns and Fenwick was downgraded to a local access route, with one half of the former four lane single carriageway converted to a cycle path.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] In an effort to prevent a repeat of the fatalities on the southern section of the road, July 2005 saw the A77 become host to the largest automatic speed limit enforcement system in the whole of the UK.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Based on the digital SPECS system rather than the traditional fixed post GATSO film cameras, gantries with automatic numberplate recognition cameras are sited on the road at intervals of between 1 and 5 miles (2 and 8 km) and measure the average speed of traffic.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The enforced zone stretches from the Bogend Toll Junction (Dundonald/Tarbolton junction) at its northern end on the dual carriageway section, down to just north of Lendalfoot; a distance of around 32 miles (51 km).
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] From 10 March 2008 a long term temporary 50 mph (80 km/h) limit from Bogend Toll to Dutch House Roundabout was introduced, following the death in October 2006 of another police officer, Constable Kevin Lowe.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Constable Lowe was on duty and en route at approximately 120 mph (190 km/h) in an unmarked car to a call at the time.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] This speed limit was to remain in force until new grade separated junctions were opened in 2014.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] As of April 2025, the speed limit is still in force.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] There have been continued efforts to improve the road in the south.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] In the early 1990s, a 2km section south of Lendalfoot and just north of Ballantrae was rediverted further back from the coastline at Snib's Cave due to coastal erosion and to provide a climbing lane to improve overtaking opportunities.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Over a decade later, another such project was the Turnberry Climbing Lane which opened in 2005, has enhanced guaranteed overtaking opportunities on the single carriageway section.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Another improvement opened in Autumn 2006, the upgraded Whitletts roundabout with traffic lights and spiral lanes.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] Climbing lanes were added at Haggstone and Drummuckloch and a 0.8-mile (1.3 km) stretch was straightened north of nearby Glenapp in autumn 2008.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] In 2011 a 1.8-mile (2.9 km) stretch was widened from Park End to Bennane.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The bypass was constructed to the west of the town from 2019 and was initially intended to open in Summer 2021.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The bypass is expected to improve traffic flow and decrease traffic through Maybole's town centre.
[src:ailsa-craig/a77-road] The A77 was formerly part of the Euroroute system, and comprised route E111.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] The **Abbot of Crossraguel** was the leader of the Cluniac monastic community of Crossraguel Abbey, near Maybole in Carrick, south-west Scotland.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] It was founded in 1260s by Donnchadh mac Gille Brigte, earl of Carrick with monks from Paisley Abbey.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] Owing to the lack of surviving records and its distance from the core of Lowland Scotland in the western Gàidhealtachd, few of the abbots are known by name.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] The abbots were replaced by commendators in the 16th century, and the abbey came to an end when its lands were taken over by the bishops of Dunblane in 1617.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] The royal warrant in 1886 which revived the office of Dean of the Chapel Royal also gave the Dean the titles of Abbot of Crossraguel and Abbot of Dundrennan.
[src:ailsa-craig/abbot-of-crossraguel] The dissolution of monasteries then caused a cessation of true abbots in the functional sense.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] There is approximately 4,000 hectares of forest within the reserve, and just under half of this is native Caledonian pine forest.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Abernethy Forest is one of the largest remaining remnant of Caledonian pine forest in Scotland.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The forest is home to a variety of birds and mammals, including Scottish crossbill, red squirrel, wildcat, red deer, black grouse, crested tit and osprey.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The Abernethy National Nature Reserve (NNR) extends to 12,755 hectares, and encompasses the majority of Abernethy Forest along with much of the adjoining landscape.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The Dell Woods section of Abernethy NNR is managed by NatureScot, whilst the rest is under the management of the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds (RSPB).
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Originally the reserve covered only the core forested section of the currently designated area, and was named Abernethy Forest NNR.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The Dell Woods section was added 1988, forming a 375 hectare extension to the existing NNR.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] In 2007, the NNR was greatly extended, becoming the new Abernethy National Nature Reserve, which extends from Abernethy Forest itself up into high Cairngorms, taking in Loch A'an and the mountains of Bynack More, Beinn Mheadhoin and the southern side of Cairn Gorm.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The Abernethy NNR is classified as a Category II protected area by the International Union for Conservation of Nature.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Over 200 vascular plant species have been recorded at Abernethy NNR, including some nationally scarce species like twinflower and creeping lady's tresses.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Heath cudweed is also present in the reserve, classed as an endangered species.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The NNR also supports a diverse population of birds, with over 70 species recorded at the Reserve.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] These include the Scottish crossbill, crested tit and capercaillie, which are all relatively rare species in Britain.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Other birds present at the Reserve include buzzards, tawny owls, great spotted woodpeckers and sparrowhawks.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] A variety of mammals have also been recorded at the reserve, including red and roe deer; red squirrels; common pipistrelles; more elusive otters and pine martens; and possible sightings of wildcats.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] NatureScot has reported fourteen species of butterfly at the Reserve, including the pearl-bordered fritillary, a UK Biodiversity Action Plan species.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The RSPB's primary conservation aim is to expand the area covered by the forest.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] On 24 August 2011 the RSPB received consent from the Forestry Commission to expand native woodland through natural regeneration and planting, since when they have begun the planting of 60,000 aspen, birch, juniper and willow trees within an area of approximately 590 hectares.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] They are also working to improve bog, moorland, scrub, rivers and mountain habitats, both within the area of the reserve and in partnership with neighbouring estates.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] Historic forestry management practices have favoured the clearance of dead wood from the forest, and the RSPB are now seeking to increase the amount of lying dead wood, and dead trees and roots.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] To this end, on 19 October 2006, the RSPB began using explosives to blast off the crowns of nine Caledonian pine trees, between 100 and 200 years old.
[src:ailsa-craig/abernethy-forest] The reserve also borders two other national nature reserves, Mar Lodge Estate and Glenmore Forest.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Craig was born in Sydney on 27 February 1917.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Her publican father died when she was two.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] She was educated at the University of Sydney, graduating with first-class honours which led to her employment at the university as a demonstrator in zoology.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] The rights to her novel, *If Blood Should Stain the Wattle*, were bought for £150 by *The Sydney Morning Herald.* Described as "told with quiet, but compelling power in the manner of Daphne du Maurier", it was serialised by that paper in April 1947.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Following its publication as a book in 1947, it was later serialised on ABC Radio.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] She then wrote a radio serial, *The Intruder*, for 2UW.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] She became a cadet journalist with *The Australian Women's Weekly*, then moved to *The Sydney Morning Herald* and was their London correspondent from 1954 to 1957 and is "believed to be the first woman to hold the position".
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Back in Australia, in 1957, she joined *Woman's Day* where she worked until 1976, in a number of roles including news editor and feature writer.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Her 1974 book, *Australia Album*, was published as a tribute to Lillian Roxon.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] She edited the compilation of photographs and wrote stories associated with them.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-journalist] Craig died on 9 December 2012, survived by her daughter and two sons and their families.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] The **Ailsa Craig Lighthouse** is an active 19th-century lighthouse located on Ailsa Craig, an island in the Firth of Clyde, just offshore from Girvan, South Ayrshire, Scotland.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] It was completed in 1886, the construction being overseen by Thomas and David Alan Stevenson.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] Initially, the lighthouse used oil-burning lamps, but by 1911, these were replaced with incandescent lighting.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] Then, in 1990, the lighthouse was automated, and a refurbishment took place in 2001, when it was converted to run on solar power.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] Ailsa Craig is also known as "Paddy's Mile Stone" as it lies halfway between the cities of Glasgow and Belfast.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] As well as being a local landmark and a well known marine navigational hazard the island is a protected bird sanctuary.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-lighthouse] In June 2018 the former lighthouse keepers' cottages, now derelict, were placed for sale by auction.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-tomato] Ailsa Craig is known for its excellent flavour, although is susceptible to the condition 'greenback', where the fruit ripens unevenly.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-tomato] The variety "Craigella" is a greenback-resistant selection of Ailsa Craig, bred by L.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-tomato] Darby of the Glasshouse Crops Research Institute, Littlehampton, and released to commerce in 1963.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig-tomato] The variety was also widely used in breeding greenhouse tomatoes in the United States, being a parent of varieties such as "Michigan State Forcing".
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island, colloquially known as "Paddy's Milestone" because it is halfway between Belfast and Glasgow, was a haven for Catholics during the Scottish Reformation in the 16th century, but is today a bird sanctuary, providing a home for huge numbers of gannets and an increasing number of puffins.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The name *Ailsa* comes from the Gaelic *Allasa(n)*, earlier *Aldasain*, which is of obscure origin.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] It has been suggested that it represents a contraction of *allt Shasann*, meaning "cliff of the Saxons" (cf.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] *airer Saxan*, "coastland of the Saxon", a name applied to southwestern Scotland in an early Gaelic text).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The "Saxons" in question would be the Northumbrians, whose territory at one time extended as far north as the Forth and Clyde.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The same applies to *Carraig Alastair* (Alexander's rock), an Irish name for Ailsa Craig.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island is sometimes known as "Paddy's Milestone", being approximately the halfway point of the sea journey from Belfast to Glasgow, a traditional route of emigration for many Irish labourers going to Scotland to seek work.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The Bass Rock is sometimes nicknamed "the Ailsa Craig of the East", although its prominence in the Firth of Forth is not as great as that of Ailsa Craig in the Firth of Clyde.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A number of features and places on the island have acquired names, Gaelic in most cases, such as Craigna'an (cliff of birds); Trammins (place of Elder trees); Balvar (big round cliff); Garryloo (rough hill) and Ashydoo (black hill).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The Swine Cave may take its name from a time when the Earl of Cassillis received part of his rent in hogs from the island.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island is approximately 16 km (8+1⁄2 nmi) west of Girvan; it is 4 km (2+1⁄2 mi) in circumference and rises to a height of 340 m (1,120 ft).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island is part of the administrative district of South Ayrshire, in the ancient parish of Dailly.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Geologically, Ailsa Craig comprises the remains of a Palaeogene pluton.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Its prominence is due to the microgranite's hardness, making it more resistant to erosion than the surrounding Permian and Triassic sedimentary rocks into which it was intruded.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The microgranite is itself intruded by a series of olivine dolerite dykes.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Ailsa Craig, along with neighbouring Arran, is part of the North Atlantic Igneous Province, a widespread system of magmatic rocks formed during the initial stages of the opening of the North Atlantic Ocean.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Boulders of distinctive Ailsa Craig microgranite known as erratics were transported by glaciers as far afield as County Donegal and Pembrokeshire.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The microgranite's unusual low-aluminium composition and crystalline texture make it particularly hard and resistant to impact, making this rock a favoured material for the manufacture of curling stones.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The "blue hone" variety is now used for the lower part of the stone which contacts the ice (the running band) while the "common green" variety is used to make the body of the stone (including the striking band).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A third variety, "red hone", is similar to blue hone but has now been exhausted.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The only surviving buildings on the island are the lighthouse on its east coast facing the Scottish mainland, a ruined towerhouse built by Clan Hamilton to protect the area from Philip II of Spain in the 16th century, and the old quarry manager's house that is used by the RSPB.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island has a fresh-water spring but no electricity, gas, sewage or telephone connections.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The chief well on the island lies above 'the Loups', and this was used by the Northern Lighthouse Board which built a cistern there and piped the water to the lighthouse complex.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The 'Horse Well' was located behind the gasworks; the 'Castle Well' stands above Ailsa Castle, and finally the Garry Loch sits higher up and once supplied water to the tenant's cottage.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Fishermen seem to have used the island for centuries, first being noted in 1549 and it is recorded that they even at one time slept beneath sails stretched over hollows on the beach.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A row of fishermen's cottages was under construction in the 1840s.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] However, the main developer died, and the project was abandoned, with the area used instead as a walled kitchen garden until the gasworks was built.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island seems to have been a part of the Barony of Knockgarron that lay in the Parish of Dailly and the then holder, Duncan of Turnberry, Earl of Carrick established the abbey of Crossraguel and endowed it with the island of Ailsa Craig to "provide for their table".
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The barony passed through several hands until it became the property of the third Earl of Cassillis in 1548.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Apart from 2 ha (5 acres) sold to the Northern Lighthouse Board in 1883, since the 16th century the island has belonged to the Earls of Cassillis.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In 1831, Archibald Kennedy, 12th Earl of Cassillis, was created the first Marquess of Ailsa, taking the title from Ailsa Craig.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In May 2011, it was announced that the island was for sale by Charles Kennedy, 8th Marquess of Ailsa, with an asking price of £2,500,000, but as of March 2013 it was unsold and the price was "offers over £1,500,000".
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] It was reported in December 2013 that an unnamed environmental trust had placed a formal bid, and in April 2014 the National Trust for Scotland was reported to be considering a bid.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] As of 2020, the island was still owned by David Kennedy, 9th Marquess of Ailsa and was leased by the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds until 2050.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Four cottages, a shed, a railway, a winch house, the main pier, and an area of adjacent land are now in the ownership of the Scottish Indian businessman Bobby Sandhu.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Mr Sandhu purchased this registered title buildings and land for £85,000 from the Argyll Group plc.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Mr Sandhu stated he wished to build a five-star hotel on the land (Title: AYR24617).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] However, the planning system apparently prevented this development.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In 1590 the shipping of the Clyde was disrupted by pirates who were said to be Highlanders, *quha lyis about Ailsay*.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Margaret Girvan ran a tearoom in a wooden building that stood next to the tacksman's cottage, famed for its pristine white table cloths and fresh scones.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Girvan kept goats in stone-built goat rees or pens on the good grazing near Garry Loch.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The feral billy goats were wont to interfere with these nanny goats and this was another reason for their demise.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] An annual hunt of the solan geese or gannets took place in the days of Robert Burns as the flesh was considered a delicacy.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Robert Burns's maternal uncle Samuel Burns was involved in the solan goose trade.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The 12 m (39 ft) high ruins of a 3-storey castle that stands on the eastern side of the island was built in the late 1500s by the Hamilton Family to protect the island from King Philip II of Spain.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island was used as a prison during the 18th and 19th centuries.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The castle has two vaulted storeys and an oven is located in a cellar with evidence of a spiral stairway that once ran to the top of the tower.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Three cinquefoils arranged in a 'V' shape are carved on the tower and indicate that the Hamiltons were linked with the structure.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] There are indications of an adjoining building that ran to the north.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Ailsa Craig was a haven for Roman Catholics during the Scottish Reformation.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In about 1587 the prominent Catholic Lord Maxwell landed on Ailsa while attempting to escape his pursuers and finding a fishing boat he attempted to reach Crossraguel Abbey, but was captured.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Andrew Knox, a Protestant minister (who later became both Lord Bishop of the Isles and Lord Bishop of Raphoe).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Barclay thereafter deliberately drowned himself in the sea or did so accidentally whilst trying to escape.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Another version states that Andrew Knox lay in wait for Hugh with nineteen others and ambushed him at the shingle beach with the result that he attempted to defend himself until he was forced back into the sea and drowned.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Beneath the Main Craig at the southern end of the island and 12 metres (39 ft) above sea level is a cave named after the supposed smuggler MacNall.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] When the cave was being cleared of guano many years ago, two stone coffins were found, both containing human bones.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Roderick Lawson (1831–1907) thought that one of the interments might be MacNall himself, but no details of this individual have yet come to light.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Ailsa Craig would have been an ideal place for the temporary hiding of contraband goods.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Lawson sees this second chapel as being a myth.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] When the lighthouse was being constructed, four stone coffins were found that may well have been associated with the first mentioned chapel, two at the tenant's house and two at the gasholder site.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The monks of Crossraguel Abbey once held the island and "places of prayer" are therefore to be expected especially with a garrisoned castle nearby; even the diminutive Lady Isle off Troon once had a chapel.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The chapel was first mentioned, along with the castle, in 1580 by Sir James Balfour.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The Lighthouse was built between 1883 and 1886 by Thomas Stevenson; it is owned by the Northern Lighthouse Board.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The lighthouse was automated in 1990 and converted to solar electric power in 2001; the island has been uninhabited since automation in 1990.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Ailsa Craig and its lighthouse feature extensively in Peter Hill's 2003 book *Stargazing: Memoirs of a Young Lighthouse Keeper*.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Two substantial foghorns with concrete housings were built in 1866, one at the north end of the island near the Swine Cave reached by 'the Loups' path and the other at East Trammins on the south end.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Both were powered by compressed air that was piped from the lighthouse, where a gas-powered compressor was housed until 1911 when oil-powered engines were installed.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] One of the compressed air pipelines can still be seen within 'the Loups' path that was constructed above it.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The compressed air cylinders that held the required store of air are still prominent features, especially at the Trammins foghorn.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Both foghorns were decommissioned in 1966 and a Tyfon fog signal was used until 1987 when improvements in ship navigation made it also redundant.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The gasworks are still a prominent feature on the island and the cable-powered tramway was partly built to haul wagons full of coal up to it from the North Port.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Two gasholders held the coal gas that powered both the compressed air pump and the lighthouse light, however in 1911 the light was converted to incandescent lighting which was powered by electricity.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The gasworks became redundant at this time.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Lawson records that oil was used to produce the gas for the lighthouse light.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The Northern Lighthouse Board's tramway had a section worked via a powered cableway that hauled wagons up from the North Port and later from the new jetty.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] This well-built tram line is largely intact and has a gauge of 914 mm (3 ft) with junction/points at the gasworks and a further set of points that led to a siding that ran down parallel to the gable end of the gasworks to presumably collect the coal ash for disposal.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The main line runs on down to the lighthouse and its ancillary buildings, taking a right-angled bend to run parallel to the southern end of the lighthouse buildings block.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] This section of the line was worked by hand and at least two wagons remain at the site together with a set of spare wheels at the gasworks.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The mineral line was built by the Ailsa Craig Granite Company Ltd. in 1909 and ran from the quarry at Kennedy's Nags via the stone crusher near the south foghorn to the Quarry Pier.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] This crudely constructed narrow gauge line was mainly horse drawn, although wagons were also moved by hand or hauled up inclines by winding engines.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The mineral railway at the quarry end had a least one siding and a mobile steam crane loaded the larger granite blocks into the wagons that were transported to the stone crusher at the Trammins near the south foghorn, smaller stones being loaded and even moved by hand.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Kerb stones and stone railway sleepers for sections of the Scotch gauge horse-drawn railway from Ardrossan to Doura were also produced.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Photographs taken in the late 19th century show the horse-drawn wagons passing in front of the lighthouse and portray the substantial railway incline and storage area.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] At times the production outstripped the storage capacity and a photograph shows at least three piles of different grades of road stone stockpiled in front of the lighthouse enclosure.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The track at the crusher had a siding that ran to the crusher and a set of points that led to the Quarry Pier main line.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The Ailsa Craig Granite Company was never a financially sound business and effectively closed in 1928.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The course of the mineral line is still evident near the quarries as a linear embankment that ends below Kennedy's Nag.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Various artefacts of the quarry enterprise remain, including concrete blocks at Kennedy's Nag and steel and concrete remnants of the stone crusher near the south foghorn.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] From the mid-nineteenth century the island has been quarried for its rare type of microgranite with riebeckite (known as "Ailsite"), which is used to make stones for the sport of curling.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] As of 2004, 60–70% of all curling stones in use were made from granite from the island and it is one of only two sources for all stones in the sport, the other being the Trefor Granite Quarry in Wales.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Ailsa Craig produced two types of granite for curling, *Blue Hone* and *Ailsa Craig Common Green*.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] *Blue Hone*, which is unique to Ailsa Craig, has very low water absorption, which prevents the action of repeatedly freezing water from eroding the stone.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In the past, most curling stones were made from *Blue Hone* but the quarry is restricted by environmental conditions that exclude blasting.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Kays of Scotland has been making curling stones since 1851 and has the exclusive rights to the Ailsa Craig granite, granted by the Marquess of Ailsa.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A "harvest" of Ailsa Craig granite by Kays took place in 2013, after a hiatus of 11 years; 2,000 tonnes were harvested, sufficient to fill anticipated orders until at least 2020.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A subsequent harvest was held in the winter of 2020.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The curling stones produced by Kays of Scotland with Ailsa Craig granite are the only curling stones approved for use in the Winter Olympic Games.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Sea eagles or erne nested at the Bare Stack until 1881 when the tenant shot the last specimen, which is preserved at Culzean Castle.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Pennant and others have noted that the only trees growing on the island are elders (*Sambucus nigra*) or *bourtrees* in the Scots dialect, found as a grove known as The Bourtrees at the Trammins on the southern end of the island.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] This visitor also rather quaintly mentions that he was surprised to find three species of "reptiles" by which he meant molluscs, namely a naked black slug, the garden snail *Cornu aspersum* and one of the common striped snails of the genus *Cepaea*.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] He speculated that they had accidentally been brought over from the mainland secreted within vegetables.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Slowworms (*Anguis fragilis*) are found on the island, although they suffered greatly when badgers and raccoons were introduced by Lord Ailsa.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The badgers did not survive long, but the raccoons bred for a number of years.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The mammal fauna included rabbits, and at one time goats, whilst pigs were bred here as food for the inhabitants.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The billy goats were shot for sport in the 19th century and no longer survive; only a mounted head of one remains at the McKechnie Institute in Girvan.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The rabbits and goats may have been originally introduced to supply food for the fishermen and were mentioned by Pennant in 1772 and by the Rev Abercummie in 1688, who called them by the old name of coneys.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The island is now a bird sanctuary, leased by the RSPB until 2050.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Rats were probably introduced via shipwrecks; supposedly, a coal boat that sank offshore was the first culprit and caused great harm to the nesting bird populations, with the puffins proving vulnerable to the extent of extinction as breeding birds.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] After a long campaign using pioneering techniques, the rats were eradicated in 1991, and now puffins are once again raising young on the island with many other benefits accruing to both the fauna and the flora.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In a small glen above Ailsa Castle, a small freshwater body known as the Garry Loch is located at an altitude of 247 m (810 ft), with a depth of at least 5.2 metres (17 ft).
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] Lawson in the 1890s records that a young lady once fell over the cliff near Craig Na'an; however, her Victorian style garments caught the wind like a parachute and she escaped with her life and some broken bones that soon knitted back together.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A visitor in a group from Stranraer was not so lucky and fell to his death on his way down from the summit.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] A shocking death was that of a young boy from Girvan who was sitting amongst loose rocks, pulling out stones and throwing them into the sea, when a very large boulder started to move and crushed him.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] The stone was too heavy to shift and help from the mainland was required to extract the body of the unfortunate victim.
[src:ailsa-craig/ailsa-craig] In 1887 a ten-year-old boy died whilst collecting eggs at the West Craigs.
